    "The inspection is your most powerful post-contract negotiation tool — but you have to use it strategically during the inspection period. Under the as-is contract, you can't demand repairs, but you can still negotiate. Here's how: **Categorize findings**: Major (safety, structural, systems) vs. cosmetic (paint, minor wear). Focus negotiation on major items only. **Your options**: (1) Request a seller credit equal to repair estimates (preferred — cleaner, no contractor coordination); (2) Request specific repairs (harder to execute, creates disputes over quality); (3) Reduce the purchase price via an addendum; (4) Accept as-is and move forward; (5) Exit the contract entirely and get earnest money back. **Strategy**: Don't nickel-and-dime every cosmetic issue — this irritates sellers and can blow up deals. Focus on items over $500 that you'd genuinely address. **Leverage**: A major finding (failed roof, failed HVAC) gives you strong leverage — the seller wants to close. A long list of minor cosmetic items gives you no leverage. **The credit vs. price reduction distinction**: A seller credit reduces your closing costs out of pocket. A price reduction reduces your loan amount (if financed). Credits are often preferable to small price reductions for buyers."
