    "What should I know about making an offer on an estate sale?",
    "Estate sales have specific characteristics that affect how you should structure and negotiate your offer. **Who you're negotiating with**: The personal representative (PR) of the estate — the executor or administrator. They may not have lived in the home and may have limited knowledge of its condition. They have a fiduciary duty to the estate's beneficiaries, meaning they must try to get fair market value. **Pricing expectations**: Estate properties are often listed at market value or slightly below to sell efficiently. Lowball offers are typically rejected — the PR can be held accountable for undervaluing the estate. Reasonable offers (within 5-8% of asking) are more productive. **As-is is standard**: Most estate sales are strictly as-is — the PR doesn't know the condition and can't make representations or agree to repairs. **Disclosure**: Sellers must still disclose known defects under Florida law — but the PR may have limited knowledge. Thorough inspection is essential. **Timeline**: PRs often want to close the estate efficiently — offering a clean, timely close (30 days) with minimal contingencies (but keep your inspection contingency) can be compelling. **Title**: Verify the PR has the Letters of Administration — they must be in place before the sale can close."
