    "What is a debt-to-income ratio (DTI) and how does it affect my mortgage?",
    "DTI (debt-to-income ratio) measures your monthly debt payments as a percentage of your gross monthly income. Lenders use it to determine how much additional debt (your mortgage) you can reasonably carry. Two types: Front-end DTI (housing ratio): monthly housing costs ÷ gross monthly income. Most lenders want this under 28-31%. Back-end DTI (total debt ratio): all monthly minimum debt payments (housing + car + credit cards + student loans + other) ÷ gross monthly income. Most conventional lenders want this under 43-45%. FHA allows up to 50% DTI in some cases. Example: Gross monthly income: $8,000. Car payment: $400. Student loans: $300. Minimum credit card payments: $200. Back-end monthly obligations: $900. Maximum back-end DTI (43%): $8,000 × 0.43 = $3,440. Available for mortgage: $3,440 - $900 = $2,540/month. Estimate loan amount: $2,540/month (P&I + taxes + insurance) at 7% might support a $300-320K purchase. How to improve DTI: Pay off debts before applying (car loan, credit cards). Avoid taking on new debt. Add income (documented side work, rental income). Use a co-borrower."
