    "What is a lien and how is it resolved before closing?",
    "A lien is a legal claim against a property that must be paid before (or at) closing. Common liens in Florida: (1) **Mortgage liens**: Existing mortgages — paid off from sale proceeds. (2) **Tax liens**: Unpaid property taxes — must be paid; title company handles through escrow. (3) **IRS federal tax liens**: Any federal tax liens against the seller attach to all their assets including the property. Must be released or subordinated before closing. (4) **Judgment liens**: Court judgments against the seller — attach to all real property in the county. Must be paid or satisfied. (5) **Mechanic's liens**: Unpaid contractors. Seller must pay off. (6) **HOA liens**: Unpaid dues, fines — resolved via estoppel certificate and payoff at closing. Resolution: all liens are identified in the title search. The title company calculates payoffs, collects sufficient funds at closing, pays off all liens, and issues title insurance after all liens are cleared."
