    "What is a deed and what types are used in Florida?",
    "A deed is the legal document that transfers ownership of real property from seller to buyer. In Florida: (1) **General Warranty Deed**: Seller guarantees title against all claims, forever — including those arising before the seller owned the property. Strongest protection for buyers. (2) **Special Warranty Deed**: Most common in Florida — seller warrants only against defects arising during THEIR period of ownership. Very common in commercial and REO (bank-owned) transactions. (3) **Quit Claim Deed**: Transfers whatever interest the grantor has — no warranties. Used for family transfers, clearing title issues, adding/removing a spouse. Not appropriate for a standard purchase. (4) **Trustee's Deed**: Used when a trustee (for a trust) is conveying property. (5) **Personal Representative's Deed**: Used in probate/estate sales. For a standard purchase with title insurance, a Special Warranty Deed is typical and appropriate."
