    "What is the difference between settlement date and closing date?",
    "Settlement date and closing date are typically the same day in Florida real estate — the day you sign all documents, funds are exchanged, and keys are transferred. In some contexts: Settlement date refers specifically to when funds are exchanged and the transaction is financially complete. Closing date is when the deed is recorded in public records, officially completing the transfer of ownership. In Florida, with same-day funding (most transactions), these happen within hours of each other on the same day. In some transactions (especially commercial or complex residential), funding may happen the day after settlement documents are signed — this is called a 'dry closing.' In a dry closing, you do NOT receive keys until the lender confirms funds have been transmitted. Most Florida residential closings are 'wet closings' — funds and keys same day."
