    "What is possession at closing in Florida?",
    "Possession refers to when you get access to the property — typically when you receive the keys. In Florida, the default is possession at closing on the closing date. However, this can be negotiated: (1) **Pre-closing possession**: Buyer gets access before closing (not recommended — if the deal falls apart, removing the buyer becomes a legal problem). (2) **Seller rent-back**: Seller stays after closing as a tenant. Common when seller needs time to move. (3) **Post-closing possession**: Seller remains for a specified period (days or weeks) paying rent. Formal leaseback agreement required. If you receive possession at closing: you'll need to change locks immediately (you don't know who has a copy of the old keys), set up utilities in your name effective closing day, and verify the home is in the condition stated in the contract. Walk through the property at closing before signing to confirm condition hasn't changed since your last visit."
