    "The Save Our Homes (SOH) cap is one of the most financially valuable features of Florida homeownership. Here's how it works:\n\n**The rule:**\nOnce your homestead exemption is granted, your property's ASSESSED value (what property taxes are calculated on) can only increase by 3% or the rate of inflation (CPI), whichever is lower — every year, regardless of how much market value increases.\n\n**The compounding benefit:**\nYear 1: Assessed at purchase price (e.g., $400,000)\nYear 2: Max increase 3% → assessed at $412,000 (not market value if higher)\nYear 5: Market value might be $480,000, but assessed might only be $437,000\nYear 10: Market value $580,000, assessed might only be $488,000\nResult: You're paying taxes on $488K while your neighbor who just bought pays on $580K\n\n**Portability (transferring your benefit):**\nIf you sell and buy another Florida homestead within 2 years:\n• You can PORT up to $500,000 of your accumulated SOH differential to your new home\n• File Form DR-501T with the new county's Property Appraiser\n• This can dramatically reduce your taxes on the new home from day one\n\n**What breaks the cap:**\n• You sell without portability transfer\n• You rent out the homestead and lose the exemption\n• You let the homestead exemption lapse\n\n**Application:**\nApply for homestead exemption by March 1 of the year after your purchase. The SOH cap starts from that point."
