    "An escalation clause is a competitive strategy for multiple-offer situations. Here's everything:\n\n**The structure:**\n'I offer [base price], but I will automatically increase my offer by [increment] above any competing offer, up to a maximum of [cap].'\n\n**Example:**\n'I offer $410,000. If there are competing offers, I will beat the highest competing offer by $5,000, up to a maximum of $435,000.'\n\nIf competitor offers $420,000 → your offer becomes $425,000.\nIf competitor offers $432,000 → your offer becomes $435,000 (the cap).\nIf competitor offers $436,000 → your cap is exceeded; you don't win.\n\n**Protective requirement to include:**\n'Escalation is contingent on seller providing a copy of the competing offer that triggers the escalation.' This prevents a fabricated competing offer.\n\n**When to use it:**\n• Agent has confirmed multiple offers are expected or received\n• You want to win without naming your ceiling upfront\n• The home is priced fairly and you're willing to go to the cap\n\n**When NOT to use:**\n• No confirmed competing offers (you give up your maximum unnecessarily)\n• You're not truly willing to pay the cap price\n• Seller specifically requests non-escalation offers\n\n**Appraisal consideration:**\nSet your cap at what you can support with an appraisal gap clause, OR only escalate to the appraised value. Don't cap above appraised value without understanding the financing implications.\n\n**Florida usage:**\nEscalation clauses are legal and common in Florida. Some sellers don't like them — if rejected, I'll guide you to a strong clean offer."
