    "The cap rate (capitalization rate) is the most widely used metric for evaluating rental properties. Here's how to calculate it and interpret it for Florida:\n\n**The formula:**\nCap Rate = Net Operating Income (NOI) ÷ Purchase Price × 100\n\n**Step-by-step for a $380,000 single-family home renting for $2,100/month:**\n\n1. Gross annual rent: $2,100 × 12 = $25,200\n2. Vacancy (7%): $25,200 × 0.93 = $23,436\n3. Operating expenses:\n   • Property taxes: $5,500/year\n   • Insurance: $4,000/year\n   • Maintenance (10% of gross): $2,520/year\n   • Property management (9%): $2,109/year\n   • Total expenses: $14,129\n4. NOI: $23,436 - $14,129 = **$9,307/year**\n5. Cap rate: $9,307 ÷ $380,000 = **2.4%**\n\n**Interpreting Florida SFR cap rates:**\n• 2-3%: Typical for single-family in major metros (Tampa, Orlando, Miami)\n• 4-5%: Better — usually smaller markets or properties that rent well relative to price\n• 5%+: Excellent for residential; more common in multifamily\n\n**Why Florida SFR cap rates are low:**\nHigh prices relative to rents. Investors accept low cap rates because of appreciation expectations, not current cash flow.\n\n**Cash-on-cash return (more relevant for leveraged investors):**\nAnnual cash flow ÷ Cash invested. On $380K with 25% down ($95K + ~$5K closing = $100K in):  If mortgage P&I is $2,010/month, monthly cash flow is negative. Most Tampa SFR investors don't cash flow today — they're appreciation investors.\n\n**The bottom line:**\nFlorida SFR investment works if you believe in 5%+ annual appreciation and can handle neutral or negative cash flow. Multifamily provides better cash flow characteristics."
